image.alt_text: Photo by CURTIS LEGACY FOUNDATION in Walpi, Arizona with @curtislegacyfoundation, and @indianartsculture. May be an image of 2 people.
image.caption:
Pulíini & Köyáme - Walpi, 1900

Hopi women traditionally had long hair, and those who were unmarried wore their hair twisted up into large spirals on either side of their heads. This represented the squash blossom - a symbol of fertility for the Southwestern tribe. 

Today, this hairstyle is still worn by unmarried Hopi girls but due to the amount of time required to create it, the style is reserved for ceremonial occasions. The hairstyle for married women was either loose or in braids.

@indianartsculture has shared a wonderful video highlighting this traditional Hopi hairstyle, which you may enjoy by visiting the link in our story & our Facebook page: www.facebook.com/CurtisLegacyFoundation

image.alt_text: Photo by The Guardian on February 12, 2022. May be an image of 5 people, people standing and text that says ''This is about progress in my life' Meet the Indigenous Bolivian skateboarders'.
image.caption:
This female skateboarding collective started “as a cry for inclusion”.

A new generation of women skateboarders in Cochabamba, Bolivia created the team ‘ImillaSkate’ in 2018.

The Imillas are known for empowering local women and skating whilst wearing the traditional Bolivian polleras dress.

The dresses are typically associated with the Indigenous women of the highland regions, after the Spanish conquest in the 16th century imposed the outfits onto the native population.

Through subsequent centuries the garment became part of the local identity and now, @imillaskate are reclaiming their roots and wearing the polleras as a piece of resistance.

“My mother has a saying – I was born wearing a pollera and I will die wearing one – and I carry on her belief,” says skateboarder Deysi.

Swipe to read more about ImillaSkate.

Photos: @luisadorr/Luisa Dörr

image.caption:
Indigenous land sovereignty is a deeply-held value of Agrarian Trust, and we have many examples of how we work to live into and promote that value:

〰️ All 501(c)(3) land trusts have provisions in their founding bylaws that outline the future of their assets in the event the organization dissolves. In that event, our bylaws ensure that all assets will transfer to Indigenous communities and communities of color as one small way to move against the perpetuation of white-led nonprofit ownership of land.  

〰️ Immediately once land is transferred into an Agrarian Commons, reparations are set up in the form of monthly direct payments to an Indigenous community that either exists there or is tied to the land. 

〰️ Where possible, we work on establishing “cultural respect and use easements” on the land where there are communities available and willing to accept that. It is our intent to ensure land is made available not just through lease tenure but through easements that provide communities land access for their ancestral lands

We acknowledge that we have much to learn and much to do to promote Indigenous sovereignty. We have engaged and must continue to engage input and perspectives from individuals of Indigenous descent through Agrarian Common Committee work and Agrarian Common Boards to determine ways to engage Indigenous communities in what we hope to be impactful ways.

With @kretakaingang, member of the @apiboficial and @alianzaglobalc, in #Scotland during #COP26

"Global Alliance of Territorial Communties @alianzaglobalc visit to Scottish local community, Argyll

Today we visited a Scottish village on the Cowal peninsula, Argyll, which is part of a movement to reform land tenure in a region where land ownership is among the most unequal in Europe.
 
The Kilfanan community of woodland crofters, seeks to be Scotland’s future forest peoples. They are waiting for the government to grant them the right to tenancy to lands that were deforested for large-scale commercial use. The crofters’ hope is to replant and manage this land so that it can be passed on for generations, a model that offers a compelling and grassroots alternative to the “green lairds” of Scotland who are purchasing forests to reap reputational and financial benefits from the sale of carbon credits. The Global Alliance of Territorial Communities delegation shared experiences with the Argyll community and a shared vision for community-led solutions to climate change."

Stötta det genuina, samiska hantverket!

Jag ogillar uttrycken "i-land" och "u-land". De antyder att alla som inte industrialiserats är under utveckling, mot industrialisering. 
Och jag ogillar industrialisering.

Tenntråd betraktar jag ofta som ett material, men det är ett hantverk i sig. Den förekommer på bland annat sydsamiska koltat och är uteslutande samiskt. Tidigare drog man tennet för hand, en process som kräver en van hand och mycket tålamod. Plötsligt blev det superpopulärt med tenntrådsarmband och efterfrågan på tenntråd ökade explosionsartat. Det dröjde inte länge innan den började dras och spinnas på fabrik och idag går det att köpa tenntråd i varenda hobby-affär. De som tillverkar tenntråd för hand idag har inte en chans.
Detsamma gäller för skinn, det är svårt att få tag på handgarvat renskinn idag om man inte har rätt kontakter. Långt färre garvar för hand, det är helt enkelt inte lönsamt. 
De maskingarvade skinnen är plastigt jämna och saknar struktur och doft. Dessutom kan de innehålla gifter och är inte speciellt miljövänliga. 
Men de är billiga!
Slöjdpriserna är och hålls låga och slöjdarna tvingas köpa industritillverkat material.
Även när annat som skor, sjalar och bälten massproduceras drabbar det i slutändan vår kultur. 
Jag anklagar dock inte samiska, större företag, tvärt om! 
Det stora problemet är konkurrensen och den skapas helt och hållet av efterfrågan. Det handlar om statusen på det genuina, samiska hantverket.

Ha detta i åtanke nästa gång du ska köpa samiska föremål!

- Satsa på genuint hantverk!
- Var beredd att betala för dig!
- Se till att det är samer som livnär sig på sin egen kultur. Våga fråga om du är osäker!

Denna sjal har Maria Rantatalo i Leppäjärvi vävt med stor omsorg, tråd för tråd. Ingenting slår den kvalitén! ❤️

Murreds våhkoe-gietjie!
Trevlig helg!

image.caption:
Thank u for sending @theurbanwalker #Repost @guardian
This female skateboarding collective started “as a cry for inclusion”.

A new generation of women skateboarders in Cochabamba, Bolivia created the team ‘ImillaSkate’ in 2018.

The Imillas are known for empowering local women and skating whilst wearing the traditional Bolivian polleras dress.

The dresses are typically associated with the Indigenous women of the highland regions, after the Spanish conquest in the 16th century imposed the outfits onto the native population.

Through subsequent centuries the garment became part of the local identity and now, @imillaskate are reclaiming their roots and wearing the polleras as a piece of resistance.

“My mother has a saying – I was born wearing a pollera and I will die wearing one – and I carry on her belief,” says skateboarder Deysi.

The dresses are typically associated with the Indigenous women of the highland regions, after the Spanish conquest in the 16th century imposed the outfits onto the native population.

Through subsequent centuries the garment became part of the local identity and now, @imillaskate are reclaiming their roots and wearing the polleras as a piece of resistance.

“My mother has a saying – I was born wearing a pollera and I will die wearing one – and I carry on her belief,” says skateboarder Deysi.

image.alt_text: Photo by Mas Verde Periódico Ecológico in Venezuela. May be an image of text.
image.caption:
Una fiesta de cumpleaños celebrada en un tepuy sagrado para los indígenas venezolanos ha generado indignación por los daños en la zona en un episodio que los críticos ven como un exceso legítimo en medio del prolongado colapso económico de Venezuela, según informa Reuters.
-
La semana pasada, los asistentes a la fiesta que celebraban el cumpleaños del empresario Rafael Oliveros fueron transportados en helicópteros a una montaña virgen conocida como Kusari, ubicada en el parque nacional Canaima en la región amazónica ecológicamente rica del sur de Venezuela, según un comunicado del grupo ambientalista SOS. Orinoco.
-
En el idioma indígena pemón, los tepuyes son venerados, incluso por su vida vegetal extremadamente rara y frágil. «Esto fue una violación a la Madre Tierra porque estas son montañas sagradas e intocables que tradicionalmente hemos cuidado, conservado y respetado, al igual que nuestros antepasados», dijo a Reuters Nazario Rosi, un anciano pemón de 63 años.
-
«Limpiaron totalmente las plantas locales», dijo Rosi, refiriéndose a los asistentes a la fiesta, y agregó que el área ha quedado como si hubiera sido rastrillada con dureza. Destacó que la cultura pemón prohíbe llegar a la cumbre de Kusari. Los invitados luciendo esmóquines y vestidos coloridos publicaron fotos y videos de la fiesta nocturna en las redes sociales, aunque muchos borraron las publicaciones a medida que aumentaba la indignación.
-
El fiscal general de Venezueal escribió en Twitter este jueves que ordenó una investigación sobre los daños causados durante la celebración. La reunión violó las reglas locales de acceso, según Rosi y Roberto Simon, otro líder indígena, quien explicó que nunca se solicitó el permiso requerido para el evento, como se hace normalmente para los proyectos de investigación científica en el parque nacional.

image.caption:
Pourquoi appelle-t-on des peuples qui préservent la biodiversité des « primitifs », comme s’ils représentaient la lie de l’humanité ? Pourquoi dévalorise-t-on leur mode de vie et glorifie-t-on notre confort, qui nous a rendu aveugles et ingrats, et dont la structure s’est fondée sur l’asservissement d’autres peuples dont des hommes corrompus ont pillé les ressources ? 

Il n’y a de sauvage chez eux que ce que nous projetons et dont nous avons peur, une peur forgée par des esprits gangrenés par le désir de domination. Non, les vrais sauvages, ce sont les fous aveuglés par l’argent et le pouvoir qui n’hésitent pas à dévorer la Terre et ses ressources, à écraser leurs semblables pour se donner, le court temps d’une vie humaine, un désolant semblant de gloire. 

Les peuples autochtones font face à d’immenses contradictions, des paradoxes à première vue insolubles entre leurs traditions et nos sociétés modernes devenues  immesurablement folles. Mais ils font partie, dans leur majorité, de ces êtres dont la connexion avec leur environnement et le respect des autres formes de vie constituent un modèle pour transformer nos mentalités, et permettre à l’humanité de se sauver d’elle-même.

Pourquoi dévalorise-t-on leur mode de vie et glorifie-t-on notre confort, qui nous a rendu aveugles et ingrats, et dont la structure s’est fondée sur l’asservissement d’autres peuples dont des hommes corrompus ont pillé les ressources ? 

Il n’y a de sauvage chez eux que ce que nous projetons et dont nous avons peur, une peur forgée par des esprits gangrenés par le désir de domination. Non, les vrais sauvages, ce sont les fous aveuglés par l’argent et le pouvoir qui n’hésitent pas à dévorer la Terre et ses ressources, à écraser leurs semblables pour se donner, le court temps d’une vie humaine, un désolant semblant de gloire. 

Les peuples autochtones font face à d’immenses contradictions, des paradoxes à première vue insolubles entre leurs traditions et nos sociétés modernes devenues  immesurablement folles. Mais ils font partie, dans leur majorité, de ces êtres dont la connexion avec leur environnement et le respect des autres formes de vie constituent un modèle pour transformer nos mentalités, et permettre à l’humanité de se sauver d’elle-même.

I'm not sure if that is from genuine ignorance or the idea that none of this effects them personally, but the reality of what is happening and the response to it all - or lack thereof - is something that should concern absolutely everyone. It really shouldn't take a far-right led occupation in order to know how f**cked up things are. Why we always gotta wait for the worse case Ontario (pun intended) before making a stance and taking action? It really ain't gotta be like this.

International borders in so-called Canada are now being blocked in Ontario, Manitoba & Alberta.

Ottawa is still occupied and it’s airport is surrounded by a vehicle blockade.

Violence and harassment continues to be a regular occurrence against community members across the country.

There has been a large number of current and ex-police, military and other government positions taking leadership roles and working to ensure plans of rhe operation are not tampered with.

US fundraising for this terrorist campaign is occurring in full public view.

Canadian Government officials have basically chosen to give up before even starting. 

Government officials, media and far-right groups in the US continue to encourage, support and fund the actions taking place across their borders. 

There's just so much to unpack here and I've been really struggling to share my thoughts on the matter. This could have been 100% prevented had people listened to the warnings so many have provided over these last 2 years. I'm unsure what to expect over the next few days and weeks, but I encourage people to remain engaged in the current events of this place you call home. We are nowhere close to seeing the end of this, nor it's effects.

Stay safe out there.
Take care of one another.
And do not let these people feel comfortable.

image.caption:
A s k 🦋

One of the greatest stretches for me on this book journey is to ask for what I desire.
.
✨asking for endorsements
✨asking for my dream book cover
✨asking for folks to share my voice 
✨asking for you to buy my book
.
It’s all been sort of scary and vulnerable and stretchy for my soul. 
.
It’s so much easier to support others!!!
.
Receptivity is good medicine too. 💛
.
At the gentle nudges of a dear friend I went to our local @chaptersnewmarket + asked if my book would be available to all of my local peeps on March 15th. 
.
It wasn’t going to be. 
.
If I hadn’t asked, I wouldn’t have known + all who wanted to get it here would miss out. 
.
Request is now in.  Books will be here. 🙏🏽
.
We walked around and I dreamed about where my book might sit on the shelves. 
.
I can’t wait to see it out in the world! 😍😍
.
Thank you to everyone who has supported this dream.  I could not do it without all of you.  Chi miigwetch - with a heart full of gratitude. (And if you haven’t - I would love to share the medicine with you) ❤️
.
33 more sleeps!!!! 🤩🤩🤩🤩🤩🦅

After the RCMP’s violent invasion of Wet’suwet’en territory, thirty-four land and water protectors, legal observers and journalists were arrested and detained. The hypocrisy of arresting peaceful land defenders on their own unceded territory, to block a pipeline that does not have the consent of Hereditary Title Holders to the land while making grand commitments to reconciliation is appalling.  Even the Canadian Supreme Court has recognized the sovereignty of Wet’suwet’en hereditary chiefs over their land.”

.

.

.

.

.

.

.
“I’ve been on a mission to Africa”
.

.
“You are attacking me”(tears)

.

.

.

.
“ I’m sick of you complaining.”
